<p>Kevin Su (b. 2000) is a composer, pianist, and computer scientist from Maryland. He is currently pursuing a PhD in music composition at the CUNY Graduate Center, where he is studying with David Fulmer.</p>

<p>Growing up, Kevin studied piano with Marjorie Lee and composition with Judah Adashi. More recently, he graduated from Stanford University, where he obtained a master’s degree in computer science, and a bachelor’s in computer science with a minor in music composition. At Stanford, he primarily studied with Francois Rose. He also studied composition and took classes with Hans Kretz and Mark Applebaum, among others.</p>

<p>Reflecting his eclectic background, Kevin is interested in exploring the relationships between music, aesthetics, technology, and politics. In another life, he might have pursued a career in computer science, specifically studying the intersection of complexity theory and algorithmic fairness. In his free time, Kevin likes to read, make coffee, and make tea.</p>

